description.text:

3D Printed Omni Wheel!

  • Insert the filament through the Double Main holes, and then leave 0.5cm on each side, then I used a soldering iron to melt the plastic flush to the side of the body, if you can't do that, just leave a bit less and either tape it or glue it.

  • You don't need any bearings

  • Uses filament to spin rollers

~ 6 hours print time total

Filaments:

  • Any ABS/PLA or other normal hard plastic
  • Some type of rubber filament such as Ninjaflex Flex TPU/Cheeta (What I used)
    Otherwise the wheels will slip around, but it still kinda works.

To Print:

NINJAFLEX TIPS

Ninjaflex can be really annoying, ESPECIALLY with the new Cura 2.3...

Please remember to change INFILL SPEED, if you dont your printer WILL jam with Ninjaflex.
By default, Cura 2.3 uses 100mm/s for infill, which will never work for Ninjaflex.

“Undesign” is a series of products from an online campaign to raise design awareness in the general public. The series features a set of glasses designs and a set of pushpin designs. They represent the design process of industrial products. Glasses and pushpins are designs that have been passed down from generations, and they still retained their classic forms. Over time, we often take these brilliant design decisions for granted. By performing “undesign” procedures on these objects, attention is drawn to the details that no one really notice in day to day life, even people who encounter these things every day. For example, the bents at the end of glasses prevent them from sliding down user’s face and the flat plain at the end of the pushpin eases the pressure on user’s finger when applied. The series follow the procedures of focusing on the core function of the product, adding to it and propose new ways to solve the same problems that it was tackling. They propose a way of looking at everyday objects and appreciate the efforts once put into its design over generations.

Maglink Concept
Maglink is a social product concept. It helps people who suffer from social phobia to approach to the society. The product catches the social moment, shaking hands as the starting point to build connection between two people. The structure of Maglink is formed by a elastic ring for the thumb and two pieces of plastic, one on the thumb and the other on the back of the hand. With two magnets, one on the thumb and one on the back of the hand, people who wear Maglink can not separate their hands easily when they shake hands. The attraction ties people who have social phobia with others, pushing them to face the society. The magnets are still removable, but the strong attraction requires users to pull the magnets very hard to separate, indicating the power of the society is hard to ignore.

“R.I.P Squirrel” is a device made to raise awareness of roadkill to the public.  Accordingly, every day in the U.S., 190 million motor vehicles hit the road, and one million animals get hit by motor vehicles, with the fact that squirrels get killed the most frequently.  Besides, it’s crucial to notice that the development of roads alters and isolates habitat and populations of wildlife, deterring the movement of wildlife, and resulting in extensive wildlife mortality.
Basically, it is designed as a tombstone, consisting of a sculpture, platform and four spikes.  The sculpture represents driving’s fatal impact to squirrels, and the platform is set as a place to put flowers on.  Last, four spikes at the bottom function as supports to prevent the device from easily being blown away.  Next time you see a dead squirrel on the road, please stop by and hold a funeral for it by putting a “R.I.P Squirrel” next to it or sticking one in dirt if there are sidewalk plantings nearby.  You can make a huge difference with a little action!

I created this as a part of a project that's main focus was to explore tics and to try to attach functions to repetitive movements that people are subconsciously prone to. I found the most common and widespread tic was the tapping tic. People often tap their fingers or feet while they work or if they are nervous. My main goal was to find a way to attach a function to that movement. I created the pedal as a sort of ironic twist, It warns you that you’re tapping by making a tapping sound with the finger and the drum. The tap register records finger tapping as small marks on the surface you’re tapping on. The marks keep you from indulging in repetitive behavior. The design can also be downloaded and used as a drum pedal. All you need is rubber bands. It’s a simple model that has many uses. I just used it to illustrate a simple concept. Unfortunately, my printer was not large enough to print my file, so I had to model it differently.

description.text:
This cap is designed to flush the engine cooling system of a Ford F-150 with a V8 engine. When flushing through a tee in the heater hose, this directs the overflow from the coolant tank to the outside of the engine cmpartment.

It looks like this will probably fit all Fords with a V6 or V8 engine and coolant recovery tank. The cap may fit other vehicles too. It has a 50mm thread diameter and 2.5mm pitch. If a Dorman 54208 replacement pressure cap will fit your vehicle, then so will this.

This was printed in PLA with 1.5mm shell thickness and works well, even with a running engine. Though ABS may perform better with hot water, I haven't tried it.

To complete this you will need a 1/2 inch PVC elbow and about 18in of PVC pipe. You should be able to press fit the parts together without glue so you can disassemble it for storage.

description.text: This is an enclosure for the optional LCD Selector used on the Sega ST-V Titan Arcade Multi-Cart. It's designed to help protect the various PCBs that make up the selector in a nice sleek package.

Notes:

I highly recommend printing the buttons with a 10mm skirt. This will make installation easier as you can drop them all in as one unit and the skirt is flexible enough to not cause any problems pushing the buttons.

There are no other special settings required to print this.

To assemble this start by removing the LCD section of the selector and putting the support block below it. This is to keep the LCD section from flexing when pushing the buttons and giving the whole thing a more solid feel. The Small nub fits in the pcb hole nearest the buttons to keep it from sliding around. Make sure all of the cables are plugged into the Selector then insert the top edge of the selector assembly into the bottom housing first so that the two pin connector at the top of the selector goes into the hole before the bottom edge of the selector is pushed down into the housing.
Insert the buttons into the top part of the housing. If you used the skirt it should stay in place fairly well, otherwise you may have to flip the whole assembly upside down while you're putting the two halves together to keep the buttons from falling out.
Make sure the wires are all fed through the opening in the side and nothing is being pinched. Once together you'll need four 30mm long M3 bolts these should be inserted from the top and gently tightened with a lot of downward pressure to help cut threads into the bottom housing.

There's probably not a lot of people who might need this, especially since the Gen1 Printrbot is no more, but I was tired of vinnivg's wonderfully small "A very compact Raspberry pi B+ and Pi 2 case" slipping out from underneath my Printrbot Simple Metal everytime I moved it, and since I am getting it ready to sell it, I wanted the new owner to have the best experience possible, so I slapped this retaining clip together in OpenSCAD to keep the incredibly slim case snug inside.

Combined with my hack to swap the Printrboard 180-degrees (putting the micro-USB port inside the base) and adding a 2.1A 5v supply (from an old mini-USB car charger that I didn't need anymore — who uses Mini-USB ?) it makes this fully-featured printer with Octoprint, auto-upload YouTube timelapses, built-in slicer (for emergencies) entirely self-contained other than the powersupply (yes, I've even ran it from a car cigarette lighter before :)

It's so clean, it will break my heart to see it go, but hopefully to a wonderful new home.

If you want to clean up your Octopi-outfitted Printrbot Simple Metal, grab this clip, and vinnieg's case, and give it a whirl.

Now more than ever, there’s a pressure to conform. Conform to the same identity, the same background, the same type of success. That pressure can manifest itself in different ways; (willful) ignorance of different kinds of people, hatred of others, an expectation of others to bend over backwards to change. Many of those who are born into that conformity expect that, if others would simply work hard enough or adopt the right attitude, they too could be happy.

“My Cute Conventional Dollhouse” seems like a straightforward project at first. All one would need to do is assemble simple parts into a typical home – one that is associated with the picture perfect, American dream-esque life. The illusion should fade quickly, as the parts can never fit together into what’s shown on the box. Instead, the user is pushed to think critically and openly in order to construct the house into a completely new format.

While technically targeted at a child, “My Cute Conventional Dollhouse” is a conceptual piece. One that urges the user to give serious thought to what society is built on, and what it teaches children.

title: Garmin cadence and speed sensor DSC10 bike seat tube bracket

description.text: I love my Garmin Forerunner watch which I use on my bike for GPS and heart rate logging. I bought the Garmin DSC10 cadence and speed sensor, but it won't fit to the bike with the standard mounting brackets or position. From a google search it seems to be a common problem. I designed this bracket to mount on the bike seat tube, picking up a magnet mounted on the bike crank. This will measure cadence only. You can still get speed from the GPS data. In addition to this bracket, you will need a M5 bolt about 40mm long, some cable ties, a slim strip of rubber to go between bracket and the sensor, a Cateye SP-6 bracket or similar to fit your seat tube with a captive nut on one side only of the bracket (they come with many Cateye lights), and a little thread lock. Assemble as the pics, adjust the angle of the bracket to the sensor before tightening the cable ties, tighten up the Cateye clamp so the captive nut pulls the non captive nut side between the nut and the bracket, a dab of thread lock on the bolt, then go ride! I might re-design the bracket to be a little curvier and not such a muck trap at the top. I have uploaded a slightly improved version of the files that I actually printed my bracket from, but they should be good. I'd like to thank my friends at http://lab3dprint.ru in Moscow who helped me with the design and the 3D printing in exchange for chocolate brownies:-)

Longer nozzel and a grip to secure the twist luer lock

I made this to solve a little problem that may be caused by JML31347's triangular joint design. Calculation of Point may be hard to do that way.

Here's how often you have to print the parts
gelenk(); // 6 x
aktuatorgelenk(); // 6 x
oberarm(); // 3 x
unterarm(); // 6 x
by28_mount(); // 3 x
actor(); // 1 x

Should be calculatable with standard deltabot algorithms..

Some additional information on what you need:

  • The robot uses three 28byj-48 stepper motors which aren't that fast but small.
  • you will need a hand full of M5x20 screws and stop nuts to mount the "gelenk" parts.
  • additionally, you need 6 4x20mm rods to mount the center arm part to the "gelenk"-parts.

Yesterday, i built the first arm and wasn't amazed by the little angle it moved, so I will rework this a little. I also decided to use only one gelenk part instead of two different. This should make it more easy to build.

description.text:
This is a model I put together for a new corexy printer I am designing. Main points were
-i wanted it to use a compatible bolt pattern to existing printers like the Tech2C hypercube I have built, which I believe is the same bolt spacing as a prusa i3.
-to use a radial fan as they are more effective at pushing air under some pressure (like through duct work)
-print fan to distribute airflow from all directions to ensure more effective cooling
-to ensure that the printed work is not hidden by the print fan ducting
-ability to mount inductive sensor
-reuse existing parts if possible

Basically to assemble you need to
-mount the main plate to the carriage first
-insert the funnel for the radial fan
-insert the duct, fix in place using self tapping screws
-bolt on your titan extruder
-fit the inductive sensor
-and finally fit the radial fan.

The basic design offers a biomimicry solution to alleviate the problem of phones slipping out of pocket by having special features on the cover that would require more application of force to remove phone. Similar to shark skin where overlapping sharp uni-directional denticles have helped reduce drag force in a specific direction. The new case work in similar fashion to increase drag in a specific direction. Sharp and downward pointing structure entangles fabrics in pocket lining, thereby increasing drag force and prevent phones from dropping out. Owing to the downward-pointing of the structure, slipping your phones into your pocket is fast and easy.

The luxury design offers a sliding case cover that can be easily slotted to cover the entire phone. In addition, during dry weather, the top face of the back cover of the phone case has been designed to allow air to enter the case and circulate around at the back of the phone, preventing overheating. For wet weather, the top of the front case is uniquely shaped to ensure water does not enter the phone cases. As opposed to most water-proofing solutions which are clumsy and prevent usage of phones. The water-proofing cases relies on understanding water flows dynamics and to direct them around the phones instead of into-the phones. Also, the case has a transparent plastic front face to enable the touchscreen function even when the phone is covered. There is a slide-in mechanism to attach the phone case onto the mounting part to provide convenience and ease of use. After further market research, we found that there is a lack of a product which incorporates all of these features, and hence, we believe this phone case to be novel in the market.
The main scope of this project will focus on designing IPhone 6 phone covers for motorcyclists.

A basic case design with uni-directional surface roughness entangles inner lining of pockets and prevent phones from slipping out of pockets. In addition, wet weather and overheating of phones are two major problems faced by motorcyclists. To prevent overheating, the luxury phone case is designed to allow better flow of air in contact with the back of the phone. Also, a unique case with slide-in transparent cover is orientated to ensure water flow away from the phones. This help phones to stay dry and functional during wet weather.

description.text:
This is a simple z-axis rod holder for a 626 bearin.  
Estabilizador para el eje Z con rodamiento 626.

comments.text: Technically speaking, this will lower print quality. When the top of the threaded rod is constrained in a bearing, its rotation causes more flex in the smooth rod...
comments.author: Shapescribe

comments.text: To be honest, I don't perceive the sypmtoms described by you. The intention of this thing is to avoid the movement on the Z axis.
comments.author: Shapescribe

comments.text: Maybe this is an issue that doesn't apply to machines using 5 mm threaded rod and 8 mm smooth rod? A while back the threaded rods were 8 mm, and placing a bearing at the other end opposite the stepper motor was a very real issue. I've made the mistake myself on one of my machines. Maybe it is more suble now.

description.text:
Pendant case for trinket version of Adafruit Gemma pendant (https://learn.adafruit.com/trinket-slash-gemma-space-invader-pendant/overview)

Wires must be cut off in order to all of them get into the case, and the back must be open to allow battery to be charged.
